The supporting cast: cut, sort, and uniq.

Three small tools fill in around grep, sed, and awk to handle most everyday text wrangling. The first is cut, which extracts columns. It works two ways: by delimiter, where you give it a separator character and the field numbers you want, or by character position, which is useful for fixed-width data. Pulling the first field out of the colon-separated password file, or fields one, three, and seven at once, is classic cut. It is simpler than awk when you do not need arithmetic, and noticeably faster on very large files.

The second is sort, which orders lines. By default it sorts in plain text order, which means the number ten sorts before the number two, because it compares character by character. A few flags fix that and more: dash n forces a numeric sort, dash r reverses it, dash u keeps only unique lines, dash k lets you sort by a particular field, and dash t sets the field separator that dash k uses. There is also dash h for human-readable sizes like one-K and two-M, and dash capital-v for version numbers.

The third is uniq, which collapses duplicate lines, and there is one crucial catch: it only collapses duplicates that are adjacent to each other. It only ever looks at consecutive runs, so in practice you almost always sort first to bring the duplicates together. Once sorted, uniq on its own removes the duplicates, uniq dash c prefixes each line with how many times it appeared, uniq dash d shows only the lines that were duplicated, and uniq dash u shows only the lines that were truly unique. Sort and uniq dash c are such close partners that you will type them together constantly.
